"Yes, sir. They must be on their way now; we gave them time to get rations from the mess." At exactly 5:00 a.m., the Exodus company was gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are deploying toward FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We must support the ongoing siege and the upcoming attack on Ianlos to crush the uprising. From there, we will have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," Shaw explained. "Gather your units and board the vehicles."
The company dispersed, each returning to their unit, and the sergeants made them mount the tanks. Cohren climbed aboard one of the armored vehicles at the front of the convoy and rejoined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he knew little about them. Sitting on the side with his legs dangling, he adjusted his pack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat mic.
"Hé Cohren, has Harris always had Snowball?" asked Nemic as they settled in.
"Are you talking about the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure of it."
Cohren glanced at one of the tanks and saw Harris with his unit. From the back of his pack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken shaking its head to observe the surroundings.
"Yeah, he always has it," Cohren replied as the tank's turret whirred open to reveal its commander.
"All the tanks were en route," declared the commander calmly but clearly from within his helmet. The engines of a platoon of tanks and Strykers roared as they began to advance. The Kronos that Cohren was on shuddered as its brakes were released and it started moving into formation. The tanks spread out in a V to cross the plains of Itania. The winter storms had frozen the marshes and forests, but the mud was still there.
After about an hour, one of the new recruits, named Orson in Cohren's memory, spoke up. "Lieutenant, have you been here since the beginning of the war, isn't that right?"
"Certainement, Operation Firestorm," replied Cohren. "We thought we could take them down in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimating is a weak word," said Nemic as he joined the conversation. "They had more weapons and men than we anticipated. They managed to destroy the UFS Revenant within the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Christ, we should see it from where we are."
"Well, I'll stand my ground for the Federation," said Orson, a bit provocatively. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You say that now, but from experience, I know that young recruits like you at eighteen take cover the moment they hear a shot," said Craith.
" I think we'll be soon informed," said Corhen, laughing. Orson said nothing more.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We detect thermal signatures approximately 300 meters away, 20 degrees right."
Cohren climbed to the top of the cart and put on his optical glasses. By activating the thermal vision, he was able to see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Uh-huh, I see them," Cohren replied via his throat mic.
"Enemies?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"It's impossible to say," Cohren declared. He activated his microphone and said, "Exodus Company, don't fire unless we fire first, make them come out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures went from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they drew closer, one of them ran toward something, grabbed it, and then rushed back to the small ridge where they were. The figures took up shooting positions.
"we have contact," Shaw shouted into the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the ridge. Bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, while soldiers leaped from their vehicles to take cover behind cover. A anti-tank missile whistled past and crashed to the ground behind the formation, exploding and sending debris flying onto one of the vehicles. Another missile struck the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew scrambled out and dove for cover as the ammunition ignited.
"Iron 1-2 et 1-3", 25 degrees right, 275 meters. "Fire!", shouted the tank platoon commander over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flew toward the ridge and exploded, sending mud and stones into the air.
"Send the Senti," Knoxx shouted, watching the ridge through his binoculars. The back of one of the Cerberus opened, and a disarmed soldier in a special helmet emerged. He barked orders into a square microphone, and two Senti, or Sentinels by their official name, rushed out. Their thin metal arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted. They were armed, but their weapons were attached to their backs.
"Are they killed or captured?" Craith asked as they watched them.
"It would seem they are being captured," Cohren said as the two Sentinels disappeared into a cloud of ash and smoke. Cries and gunshots echoed from the ridge, but quickly ceased. Moments later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots dragged along the ground. Once safe among the squad, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he collapsed into the mud and snow.
Shaw walked toward the individual, who was beginning to get up. He turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, commander," said the Sentinel. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing beside him. "Both of you, would you be so kind as to get rid of this man?"
